[Cutaneous leishmaniasis is highly endemic in Pakistan and especially in the eastern provinces and tribal areas bordering Afghanistan, and ProMED-mail has repeatedly reported the situation (see previous postings listed below).

A recent, comprehensive global review of leishmaniasis, including the situation in Afghanistan, can be found in: Alvar J, VÃ©lez ID, Bern C, et al. Leishmaniasis worldwide and global estimates of its incidence. PloS One. 2012;7(5):e35671. Available at: http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0035671.

The 2 types of leishmania causing cutaneous leishmaniasis in Pakistan are _Leishmania tropica_, which mainly spreads from human to human, and _L. major_ which is transmitted from a reservoir in small rodents. Genotyping of leishmania from patients will help elucidate the focus of the present outbreak, and the main control efforts should target the sandfly vector. - Mod.EP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4167556,19537.]
